Part 1: Data

The General Social Survey (GSS) is a nationally representative survey of adults in the United States conducted since 1972. The GSS collects data on contemporary American society in order to monitor and explain trends in opinions, attitudes and behaviors. The GSS has adapted questions from earlier surveys, thereby allowing researchers to conduct comparisons for up to 80 years. More information can be found on the web site of the GSS project https://gss.norc.org/About-The-GSS

To safeguard the health of staff and respondents during the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2021 GSS data collection used a mail-to-web methodology instead of its traditional in-person interviews. Research and interpretation done using the data should take extra care to ensure the analysis reflects actual changes in public opinion and is not unduly influenced by the change in data collection methods. For more information on the 2021 GSS methodology and its implications, please visit https://gss.norc.org/Get-The-Data

GSS collects data using multi-stage survey design, which needs to be considered in order to generalize to the whole US population. To make my results generalizable I’m going to use the survey analysis library https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/survey/index.html

This is observational study so only correlational inference can be made.

Part 2: Research question

Health inequity

The bases for inequalities, or determinants of health, are many. Margaret Whitehead developed the concept of health equity adopted by EURO/WHO.

Whitehead defines health inequities as “differences in health which are not only unnecessary and avoidable but, in addition, are considered unfair and unjust.”

According to Whitehead, health inequalities determined by these categories are more likely to be considered avoidable and unfair:

  • health-damaging behavior in which the degree of choice of lifestyles is severely restricted;

  • exposure to unhealthy, stressful living and working conditions;

  • inadequate access to essential health services and other basic services;

  • natural selection, or health-related social mobility, involving the tendency for sick people to move down the social scale. (Carter-Pokras and Baquet 2002)

Within the US healthcare system these differences have most convincingly been demonstrated across racial and ethnic lines (whites vs minorities); however, disparities based on other categorizations have also been described, including geography (urban vs rural), gender (male vs female), socioeconomic status (poor vs nonpoor), and age (nonelderly vs elderly).(Gibbons 2005)

COVID-19 impact.

Although the COVID‑19 virus infects those exposed indiscriminately, exposure risk and the severity of its health, social and economic impacts are not being felt equally.

COVID‑19 and its containment measures have exacerbated current and created new vulnerabilities through three key mechanisms: unequal socioeconomic impacts arising from both the health effects of COVID‑19 and their inequities and COVID‑19 containment measures; and the bidirectional effects between the unequal socioeconomic impacts of COVID‑19 and non-COVID‑19-related health inequities. https://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/health-determinants/social-determinants/publications/2020/health-inequity-and-the-effects-of-covid19-2020

I’m going to look at the relationship between socioeconomic status (defined by class variable) and health (defined by health variable) using GSS cross-sectional data. Interesting question for me is how this trend changes over time and especially in the 2021 year data.

  • health

    Would you say your own health, in general, is excellent, good, fair, or poor?

  • class

    If you were asked to use one of four names for your social class, which would you say you belong in: the lower class, the working class, the middle class, or the upper class?

Part 4: Inference

Chi squared

Condition for inference using chi squared is satisfied only for the main dataset:

  • independence - observations are independent between and within the groups, data is not paired (from GSS survey design), sample size <10% of the population

  • number of observations in each of the groups >5.

H0: distribution of health is independent of class, all variations is due to chance \(\pi_{1} = \pi_{2}= \pi_{3}= \pi_{4}\)

H1: distribution of health is not independent of class \(\pi_{1} \neq \pi_{2} \neq \pi_{3} \neq \pi_{4}\)

chi<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_a_design, statistic = 'Chisq')
chi 
## 
##  Pearson's X^2: Rao & Scott adjustment
## 
## data:  svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_a_design, statistic = "Chisq")
## X-squared = 1775.6, df = 9, p-value < 2.2e-16

P-value is almost zero which allow us to reject H0 and conclude that distribution of health is not independent of the class

Statistic yearly dynamic

This data isn’t very reliable because some groups has less then 5 observations but it is anyway interesting to look at. For each year I calculated 4 different types of statistic:

The default (statistic="F") is the Rao-Scott second-order correction. The p-values are computed with a Satterthwaite approximation to the distribution. The alternative statistic="Chisq" adjusts the Pearson chisquared statistic by a design effect estimate and then compares it to the chisquared distribution it would have under simple random sampling. The statistic="Wald" test is that proposed by Koch et al (1975) and used by the SUDAAN software package. It is a Wald test based on the differences between the observed cell counts and those expected under independence. The adjustment given by statistic="adjWald" reduces the statistic when the number of PSUs is small compared to the number of degrees of freedom of the test. Rao and Thomas (1990) compare these tests and find the adjustment beneficial. From https://r-survey.r-forge.r-project.org/survey/html/svychisq.html

years <- unique(gss$year)
f_all <- NULL

for (i in years) {
  gss_design <-svydesign(id = ~vpsu, 
                           strata = ~vstrat, 
                           data = subset(gss, 
                                          !is.na(class) & 
                                          class!="no class" & 
                                          year == i &
                                          !is.na(health)), 
                           weights = ~wtssall, 
                           nest = TRUE)

    gss_design <- update(gss_design,class= droplevels(class))
    chi1<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_design, statistic = 'Chisq')
    chi2<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_design, statistic = 'F')
    chi3<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_design, statistic = 'Wald')
    chi4<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss_design, statistic = 'adjWald')
    
    df<-data.frame(year=i,
                   Chisq_st = chi1$statistic,
                   F_st = chi2$statistic,
                   Wald_st = chi3$statistic,
                   adjWald_st = chi4$statistic )
    row.names(df) <- i
    f_all <- rbind(f_all,df)
}

#adding 2021
   chi1<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss2021_design, statistic = 'Chisq')
   chi2<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss2021_design, statistic = 'F')
   chi3<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss2021_design, statistic = 'Wald')
   chi4<-svychisq(~class + health, design = gss2021_design, statistic = 'adjWald')
    
    df<-data.frame(year=2021,
                   Chisq_st = chi1$statistic,
                   F_st = chi2$statistic,
                   Wald_st = chi3$statistic,
                   adjWald_st = chi4$statistic )
    row.names(df) <- i
    f_all <- rbind(f_all,df)

f_all %>% 
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x=year,y=Chisq_st,color="Chisquared"),size=1) + 
    geom_line(aes(x=year,y=2*F_st,color="2X Rao-Scott"),size=1) +
    geom_line(aes(x=year,y=2*Wald_st,color="2X Wald"),size=1) +
    geom_line(aes(x=year,y=2*adjWald_st,color = "2X adjusted Wald"),size=1)+
    scale_color_manual(name = "statistics", 
                     values = c(
                       "Chisquared" = "#0072b2", 
                       "2X Rao-Scott" = "#e69f00",
                       "2X Wald" = "#56b4e9",
                       "2X adjusted Wald" = "#cc79a7"
                       )) +
    geom_point(aes(x=year,y=Chisq_st)) +
    geom_text(
      aes(x=year,y=Chisq_st),
      label=f_all$year, 
      position = position_nudge(x = 1,y = -1),  
      size=3
    )

Part 5: Opinion

GSS provides a rich source of information about opinion trends. As a conclusion I would like to look at how the situation with health disparity is reflected in mass consciousness by one example:

natfare

We are faced with many problems in this country, none of which can be solved easily or inexpensively. I’m going to name some of these problems, and for each one I’d like you to name some of these problems, and for each one I’d like you to tell me whether you think we’re spending too much money on it, too little money, or about the right amount. First (READ ITEM A) . . . are we spending too much, too little, or about the right amount on (ITEM)? K. Welfare
